We now expect a 25bp cut from the Fed in September as our baseline, followed by quarterly cuts of 25bps to a terminal of \(2.75 - 3.0\%\) by end- 2026. We do not view a September cut as a certainty — August payrolls of 225k and another clear acceleration in tariff- related inflation could keep them on hold. Conversely, we believe a larger up- front cut would come only with sizeable payroll declines. The Fed could also see dissents against rate cuts in September. read more

We're constructive on USD assets, but not USD. We are equal- weight in equities (US over Rest of World), overweight in core fixed income, and underweight in other fixed income. Despite concerns, US markets are still unmatched in size and liquidity. But rising policy uncertainty will likely drive foreign investors to up their FX- hedging ratios, putting pressure on the USD. Given growth and tariff risks, we favor quality cyclical stocks and investment- grade over high- yield credit. read more

Clearly, MSCI Europe is less exposed to OBBBA's relevant cash tax provisions than the S&P, but pockets of exposure still exist, and future benefits could accrue. Broader exposures depend on (1) R&D levels, and capex- to- sales; (2) the proportion of this R&D and capex spent in the US; (3) a complex array of company- specific cross- border tax considerations; and (4) certain sector considerations, e.g. regulated utilities are not exposed to bonus depreciation. read more

The whole value chain is progressing rapidly, driving intelligent/humanoid robots from showcase to real adoption. At the same time, we believe that as adoption ramps up, mass production requirements will raise the bar for humanoid value chain companies. We expect stock drivers to evolve from simply "catalysts" to "catalysts + earnings contribution." China- based components names to play this theme include Innovance, Leaderdrive, Shuanghuan, Hengli, Sanhua, Tuopu, Hesai, Horizon Robotics, and CATL. read more

The global biotech sector is at a pivotal moment as China transitions from traditional generics manufacturing into the global innovation ecosystem — China biotech is no longer merely a regional story. We believe China- originated assets could account for \(35\%\) of US FDA approvals by 2040, up from just \(5\%\) today, generating an estimated US \(220 billion in ex- China revenue. While geopolitical tensions and certain policies by the US and China pose potential risks to the flow of innovation, we think a likely outcome is "co- petition" – a blend of competition and collaboration – as the global biopharma industry grapples with the dual imperatives of innovation and resilience. read more

Our view is that the post- pandemic US labor market is not breaking, but instead transitioning to a more sustainable pace, heavily influenced by labor supply shifts. Tighter immigration policy and slower population growth mean the labor force is not growing like it used to. With limited workforce growth, the "breakeven" pace of payrolls is much lower. The August US employment data should indicate whether the weakness in the labor market over the summer was a transitory response to the April 2 announcements, or a signal of the start of genuine deterioration. read more

- French PM loses the vote of confidence on September 8, our baseline is that a new PM could be appointed soon afterward. We stress that uncertainty is likely to be elevated in all potential scenarios for several months. It remains to be seen, for instance, whether a new PM would be able to pass a budget before the end of December. And with local elections planned in March 2026, political uncertainty could extend into the first few months of next year. We expect low growth in 2026 (0.6% Y/Y) and, at most, limited fiscal consolidation. read more

China Economics: Contrasting China's Fiscal Policy with the USPost- pandemic, public debt ratios have surged in both China and the US to their respective all- time highs (ex- Covid), reaching \(119\%\) of GDP in both economies. China maintains its tilt toward investment while the US boosted household transfers post- Covid, leading to divergence in economic outcomes. China has experienced nine consecutive quarters of deflation, while inflation has remained above target in the US for the last four years. For China, anti- involution (i.e., efforts to diminish unproductive excess competition among enterprises) should help improve pricing power for select sectors but likely not in aggregate; persistent deflation is likely to keep the debt- to- GDP ratio rising. For the US, the fiscal policy setup is adding to overall policy uncertainty. Higher macro risk premium means the USD stays weak. read more

With Fed rate cuts seemingly imminent, we expect both Treasury yields and USD to make new lows in the fall. We continue to suggest investors stay long duration via UST 5y notes and continue to play for steeper curves via UST 3s30s yield curve steepeners. We also continue to recommend short USD positions. We suggest investors position for EUR and JPY to gain against USD. read more

US Agency MBS: It's a Long Story - Mortgages, Just Say YesWe recommend buying MBS. Valuations have tightened, but the odds of a negative fundamental backdrop (Fed on hold for longer) are much lower, and mortgages are wide to / have underperformed most other asset classes. We think bank demand is likely to pick up as banks have more conviction around the policy rate. read more

US Consumer: Back- to- School 2025 - Getting High MarksSeveral likely spending tailwinds and encouraging early datapoints make us positive on the Back- to- School season. From a macro perspective, we expect a solid BTS season this year, though partially driven by the acceleration in prices for tariff- exposed BTS categories. Within Retail Softlines, we expect a strong BTS, with nearly every datapoint we track currently positive. We see American Eagle and Abercrombie as potential winners and Foot Locker and Macy's as possible laggards. We are also optimistic on Hardlines as the consumer seems willing to spend while remaining value- focused. read more

We continue to see attractive midterm prospects for the Europe Healthcare industry but revise our order of preference post- 1H25 performance. We take profits on Biomerieux and downgrade to EW as near- term EPS risk could cap multiple expansion, while upgrading DiaSorin to OW on improving growth momentum. read more

We believe China's Financials sector is entering a relatively benign operating period after a 10- year financial clean- up that has reduced perceived high risk financial assets from \(\sim 30\%\) of total financial assets in 2017 to \(\sim 5\%\) 2025. Stabilization of financial asset yields, together with further moderation in credit costs over time, should support high- single- digit profit growth for the sector, with double- digit profit growth at Insurance firms and "growth" banks. As a result, we think the sector's discount to the overall market will narrow further. read more

Analysis of AWS's capex, the resulting expected data center square footage growth, and AWS's historical revenue per square foot gives us more conviction that AWS growth has the potential to accelerate to \(20\% +\) in 2026. This is ahead of our base model and should be a key driver of AMZN's multiple. read more

We continue to take CEO Lip Bu Tan at his word - this will be a challenging turnaround with no quick fix, while the stock mostly reacts to "quick- fix" narratives. Government support can be helpful, but further cash infusions would not be our focus - in our view, the CPU roadmap has to be the focus and the government's focus on foundry could prove a distraction. We remain EW INTC. read more

We think the bears focus on recent trends and dislike Li Ning's slower- than- peers growth, single brand that is difficult to differentiate, and lack of fast- growing categories (e.g., outdoor). We remain OW even after the recent rally: At \(14\times\) 2025e P/E, we see favorable risk/reward. We see a high likelihood that margin recovery will be the key earnings driver for the next few years. Li Ning's sales growth is still subject to China's macro environment, so we bake in conservative assumptions. But its "defensive approach" and "focus on core" should lead to future operating leverage. read more
